In refuting the suggestion that Mrs. Tripp betrayed the trust of a vulnerable woman half her age, a person close to Mrs. Tripp's legal team suggested that Mrs. Tripp had tried several times last fall to end her friendship with Ms. Lewinsky, who would sometimes call and e-mail Mrs. Tripp 20 times a day.
 The tapes that Linda Tripp secretly made of telephone conversations with Monica Lewinsky may not be released next week with other evidence given to Congress by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde said Thursday.
 Maryland prosecutors have asked the federal judge overseeing a grand jury investigation of President Clinton for access to Linda Tripp's secret tape recordings of Monica Lewinsky, a newspaper reported.
A conservative legal group, Judicial Watch, had argued for the material to be made public alleging that political pressure from the Clinton administration drove the grand jury to investigate whether Ms. Tripp broke Maryland law by recording phone conversations with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
 The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Dec. 19 : The attempt by a Maryland prosecutor to try Linda Tripp on state wiretapping charges for secretly tape-recording her telephone conversations with Monica Lewinsky has revived passions that have been dormant since President Clinton's impeachment trial.
 Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr came under increased criticism Wednesday as a Democratic senator questioned his conduct of the Monica Lewinsky investigation.
